\begin_layout Section
Contract Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contract Law is a fundamental aspect of legal studies that deals with the
 rules and principles governing agreements between parties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the classification of contracts helps in grasping the legal
 implications and obligations that contracts impose on the parties involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification Depending on the Type of Contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Named contracts
\series default
 have specific designations and are recognized by law, such as sales, leasing,
 service contracts, work, deposit, and company agreements.
 The advantage of named contracts is that they are already established by
 law, which can be either supplementary (optional) or mandatory (compulsory).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Unnamed contracts
\series default
, on the other hand, are complex and unique (
\emph on
sui generis
\emph default
).
 These contracts do not fit into the predefined categories and may require
 special consideration and interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's important to note that this classification does not bind judges: there
 is 
\series bold
judicial discretion
\series default
.
 In cases of mistakes or dissimulation (concealment of truth), a judge has
 the discretion to interpret the contract beyond its classification.
 For example, a contract may be classified as a service contract, while
 the reality behind the contract is a work relation.
 In this case, the judge can interpret the contract as a work contract,
 even if it classified by the parties as a service contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contracts can also be classified as 
\series bold
general agreements
\series default
 or 
\series bold
accessory agreements
\series default
, highlighting the primary versus supplementary nature of the contractual
 obligations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification Depending on the Object
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Bi-/Multi-Lateral (Synallagmatic) Agreements
\series default
: according to the Article 1106 of the Civil Code, synallagmatic agreements
 create recriprocal obligations for all parties involved.
 This means each party has duties towards the others, establishing a mutual
 dependency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Unilateral Agreements
\series default
: conversely, Article 1106 of the Civil Code also mentions that unilateral
 agreements impose obligations on one party alone.
 This type of contract involves a single party's commitment without requiring
 a reciprocal promise from another party.
 For example, I can post an offer of a reward in exchange for a lost wallet,
 setting up an unilateral agreement that stipulates that the reward will
 be issued once my wallet is found.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This distinction is particularly relevant for mechanisms such as the 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exception d'inexécution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
 (defense of non-performance), which includes suspension, resolution, and
 risk theory.
 These mechanisms allow parties to respond to breaches of contract in a
 manner that reflects the mutual or unilateral nature of their agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof of contracts and their terms is subject to the dual original exigency,
 as stated in Article 1375.
 This means that establishing the existence and specifics of a contract
 often requires adherence to strict legal standards, emphasizing the importance
 of clear, mutual agreements and understanding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Free-of-Charge Contracts or Contracts Drawn Up in Return for Payment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contracts can be also classified based on the presence or absence of a financial
 consideration:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Free-of-Charge Contracts
\series default
: these are agreements where one party benefits without a requirement to
 provide a financial return to the other party.
 For example, in a donation, one party, the donor, transfers ownership of
 property or a sum of money to another party, the donee, without expecting
 anything in return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Contracts Drawn Up in Return for Payment
\series default
: these involve transactions where services of goods are exchanged for payment.
 They can be either reciprocal or unilateral in nature, depending on whether
 both or one party is obligated to provide something of value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within the realm of return-for-payment contracts, further subdivisions include
 commutative and aleatory contracts, both of which are forms of synallagmatic
 agreements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Commutative contracts
\series default
: these contracts involve exchanges where the reciprocal advantages are
 immediately known and can be evaluated.
 Each party knows what to expect and what is expected in return.
 For example, a sales contract, in which one party sells a product to the
 other party for a certain amount of money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Aleatory contracts
\series default
: these are characterized by uncertainty.
 The advantages or obligations depend on an uncertain event (
\emph on
aléa
\emph default
).
 The risk can be inherent to the contract's nature or introduced by the
 parties' agreement.
 The principle here is that hazard nullifies tort (
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

l'aléa chasse la lésion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
), meaning a contract cannot be nullified due to the absence of cause or
 because of an unfair disadvantage (
\emph on
lésion
\emph default
), except in specific cases related to the aleatory element, like in life-contin
gent annuities (
\emph on
rente viagère
\emph default
).
 These contracts reflects an economic application of game theory, where
 the principle of large numbers does not apply uniformly, affected by the
 parties' quality.
 An example of an aleatory contract is a life insurance policy, where the
 obligations of the parties involved depend on an uncertain event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Instantaneous Contracts and Contracts of Continuing Performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The execution timeline of contracts introduces another layer of classification:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Instantaneous contracts
\series default
: these are executed in a single action or step.
 Once the agreed exchange is made, the contract is considered fulfilled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Contracts of continuing performance
\series default
: these require a certain period to be fully executed, establishing ongoing
 obligations over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interest of distinguishing between these types lies in the implications
 for declaring invalidity.
 For contracts of continuing performance, rescinding or terminating the
 agreement can significantly impact the contractual relationship, affecting
 how and when parties can exit the contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distinction between instantaneous and continuing performance contracts
 is 
\series bold
relative
\series default
.
 A series of instantaneous contracts can collectively resemble a continuing
 performance contract, especially in scenarios like a processing contract
 or in the event of bankruptcy, where the ongoing nature of obligations
 comes to the forefront.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Contracts That Are Limited in Time or With A Termination Date
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contracts of continuing performance often include provisions for 
\series bold
tacit renewal
\series default
.
 This means that even without explicit agreement, the contract can automatically
 renew under certain conditions.
 Such provisions allow for a seamless continuation of the agreement, provided
 both parties continue to fulfill their obligations without objection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contract might be set without a specific deadline, being its end dependent
 of a particular event.
 According to a ruling by the Cour de Cassation on October 28, 1992, the
 event triggering the contract's end must be independent of the parties'
 will.
 This ensures the contract's continuity is not arbitrarily controlled by
 either party, providing a fair and predictable framework for its duration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For contracts without a fixed duration, unilateral termination is generally
 permissible at any time.
 However, this termination must not be abusive (
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in case of excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
) and should be executed with a reasonable period of advance notice.
 The flexibility allows parties to exit agreements when they no longer serve
 their mutual interests, provided they do so considerately and fairly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Article 1738 of the Civil Code provides a legal framework for tacit renewal,
 especially in the context of written leases.
 If, at the expiry of the lease, the lessee remains in possession of the
 property with the lessor's acquiescence, a new lease is formed under the
 conditions of an unwritten lease, unless specifically excluded by the initial
 agreement or by the contract's nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general rule for renewed contracts is that they continue under the same
 conditions as the original, except for certain clauses that may be considered
 divisible or specific to the initial term.
 Each renewal is treated as a new contract, allowing for adjustments and
 updates to reflect the parties' current circumstances and intentions.
 Notably, unless explicitly agreed otherwise, a renewed contract under Article
 1738 does not have a predetermined termination date, reinforcing the importance
 of specifying any desired changes or limitations during the renewal process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All these rules are meant to protect the interests of the weaker party in
 contractual relationships, such as in rental agreements or employment contracts.
 By ensuring that renewals and terminations adhere to principles of fairness
 and reasonable notice, the law aims to maintain balanced and equitable
 agreements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification Depending on the Status of the Different Parties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
intuitu personae 
\emph default
(depending on the person) nature of certain contracts highlights the importance
 of personal considerations in the formation of agreements.
 In such contracts, the specific characteristics or qualifications of the
 parties involved are crucial, and a mistake regarding the identity or essential
 qualities of a party (
\emph on
erreur sur la personne
\emph default
) can be a reason for nullifying the agreement.
 However, the importance of personal considerations has diminished over
 time due to the growth and frequency of commercial exchanges, making it
 a less dominant factor in many contractual relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The Status of 
\emph on
Consumer 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
Professional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distinction between a consumer and a professional is objectively defined
 within consumer law, as demonstrated by the Cour de Cassation's decision
 on May 15, 1984, concerning a patient's relationship with a doctor.
 This distinction is pivotal in determining the applicability of specific
 protections and obligations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jurisprudence has further clarified this distinction, as seen in the case
 of May 3, 1998, where a priest purchasing a photocopier for parish use
 was not considered a professional act due to its linkage to the parish's
 activities.
 Conversely, acts directly related to professional activity are deemed 
\emph on
professional
\emph default
.
 This was adjusted from earlier jurisprudence, which considered professional
 acting outside their area of expertise as consumers, as in the case of
 May 25, 1992, regarding a reseller buying an alarm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Special rules apply to loans for consumers, where the object of the loan
 is a critical consideration.
 Since 1993, consumer rights have been codified, encompassing rules on advertisi
ng, information, cooling-off periods, and retraction, alongside mechanisms
 for control and enforcement against unfair terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The codification of consumer rights aims to balance interests and promote
 
\emph on
legal solidarism
\emph default
, though it also introduces some challenges.
 It disrupts traditional contract law principles, like consent, offer and
 acceptance, and can be seen as unstable, bureaucratic, formalistic, and
 rigid.
 Critics argue that the emphasis on consumer protection can hinder economic
 development by introducing additional costs and complexities.
 Special attention is given to adults incapable of managing their affairs
 independently, whose protection is considered very important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification Depending on the Mode of Formation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Consensual contracts
\series default
: these are based on the simple agreement of the parties involved.
 The essence of consensual contracts is that they are formed by the mutual
 consent of the parties regarding the contract's terms, without the need
 for any formalities or the transfer of a thing.
 This principle is foundational in French law, as highlighted in Article
 1172, which underscores the importance of consent in contract formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Real contracts
\series default
: real contracts require the transfer of a thing (an object or right) for
 the contract to be considered formed.
 Examples include loans (Article 1875), deposits (Article 1919), and pledges
 (Articles 2071).
 These contracts are not complete until the specified object has been transferre
d from one party to the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Solemn contracts
\series default
: solemn contracts require specific formalities to be fulfilled for the
 contract to be valid.
 These formalities could include written documentation, registration, or
 other legal procedures.
 The solemnity aspect underscores the contract's importance, ensuring clarity
 and legal compliance.
 For example, a real estate contract that requires a notarized deed to be
 legally valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Negociated contracts
\series default
: these contracts are the results of back-and-forth negotiations between
 the parties, allowing for terms and conditions to be discussed and agreed
 upon before the contract is finalized.
 This type reflects a social reality where parties have equal bargaining
 power to shape the contract's content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Membership (adhesion) contracts
\series default
: membership contracts are standard form contracts where one party (typically
 a business or service provider) sets the contract terms, and the other
 party (usually a consumer) has little to no ability to negotiate.
 The consumer can aither accept the contract as is or reject it entirely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the foundational role of Common Law principles in contracts, the
 issue of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unfair terms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has gained prominence, addressing concerns over potential imbalances in
 membership contracts.
 This has led to specific regimes in some foreign legal systems to protect
 parties, particularly consumers, from unfair or abusive terms that one
 party might impose due to a superior bargaining position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distinction between
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Notion of Contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Historical Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Roman contracts and non-contractual obligations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Roman legal system introduced the notion of contracts with four primary
 consensual contracts: sale, mandate, rental, and company.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It also recognized non-contractual obligations such as guardianship and
 tort sources, expanding the scope of legal obligations beyond formal agreements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Evolution from individualism to opposing interests
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1804, the notion of contract was heavily individualistic, anchored in
 the theory of free will (
\emph on
autonomie de la volonté
\emph default
).
 Over time, legal theory has shifted towards considering 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

opposing interests
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, acknowledging the dynamic and often conflicting nature of contractual
 relationships.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Unilateral Deed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A unilateral deed, or unilateral declaration, involves a situation where
 a single party's declaration or promise creates an obligation upon them,
 without requiring acceptance or an act of performance by another party
 for it to take effect.
 The obligation is self-imposed by the declarant's will alone, and it must
 be communicated to the person it affects, but it does not form an agreement
 between two parties.
 For example, a promise to make a donation to charity can be considered
 a unilateral deed.
 If an individual publicly announces their intention to donate a certain
 amount to a charity, they have created an obligation for themselves through
 their declaration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A unilateral deed is distinguised from a unilateral contract by requiring
 only one party's will to create an obligation, while in a unilateral contract,
 the obligation is conditional upon the performance of a specified act by
 another party, essentially forming an agreement once the act is performed.
 However, for such a deed to be valid, the impacted individual must be informed,
 and there exists debate over the validity of self-imposed obligations.
 An example is a public promise to reimburse, which can be revoked until
 the promised act is accomplished.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Mandatory Conventions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-mandatory conventions, such as debt forgiveness, do not create obligations
 and are theoretically distinct from contracts, despite being effective
 in practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example are acts of kindness and accommodation, which are actions
 taken out of goodwill or to accommodate someone else, such as providing
 a ride or assisting a third party withoyt expecting anything in return.
 Initially, these acts may not create legal obligations.
 However, if they lead to harm or loss, they could result in indemnity claims.
 Over time, such acts might be interpreted through a quasi-contractual lens,
 especially if they resemble actions typically covered by contracts, like
 providing services under a free services contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Gentleman's agreements
\series default
 are informal agreements based on the honor of the parties involved, rather
 than legal obligations.
 They are characterized by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Basis in honor
\series default
: the primary foundation of a gentlemna's agreement is the personal integrity
 and honor of the parties.
 Such agreements are common between states or friends, where formal contracts
 are either impractical or deemed innecessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Legal enforceability
\series default
: while the legal doctrine often views these agreements as non-binding due
 to the lack of legal obligations, courts sometimes consider the common
 intentions of the parties involved.
 If it appears that the parties intended to create a binding commitment,
 a court may enforce the agreement based on those intentions, despite the
 informal nature of the agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Letters of intent
\series default
 are documents used during the preliminary stages of negotitations to outline
 the key elements of a proposed agreement and the parties' intent to continue
 discussions.
 They serve several important functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Clarification of intentions
\series default
: they help both parties clarify their intentions and the main points of
 the deal under considetation, providing a roadmap for future negotiations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Non-binding nature
\series default
: typically, they are non-binding regarding the final agreement, meaning
 they do not legally obligate the parties to finalzie the deal.
 However, certain parts of a letter of intention, such as confidentiality
 clauses or exclusivity agreements, may be binding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Ambiguity and enforcement
\series default
: the notion of letter of intention is ambiguous because, while they signify
 a willingness to engage in negotiations, the extent to which they are enforceab
le varies.
 If a letter of intention is detailed and includes terms that suggest a
 commitment, courts may interpret it as binding, depending on the parties'
 apparent intent and the document's specific language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Avant-Contracts (Preliminary Contracts)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Avant-contracts are preliminary agreements that outline the terms and conditions
 under which the parties intend to enter into a definitive contract in the
 future.
 They are binding to the extent that they commit the parties to continue
 their negotiations based on the terms outlined in the avant-contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several types:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Unilateral promise to contract
\series default
: gives one party, the beneficiary, the option to enter into a contract
 within a specified time frame.
 This promise grants the beneficiary a personal right against the promisor,
 which becomes enforceable once the option is exercised.
 Before acceptance, it's a personal right; after acceptance, it transforms
 into an indefeasible right subject to forced execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Synallagmatic promise
\series default
: involves mutual commitments from both parties to enter into a contract
 upon meeting certain conditions or formalities.
 This type of acant-contract is immediately binding as a promise of sale,
 effectively considered equivalent to a sale, as per Article 1589 of the
 Civil Code.
 However, the execution of the definitive contract may depend on completing
 specific formalities or conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Crossed promises
\series default
: consist of two unlitateral promises that intersect; for example, one party
 promises to sell, and the other promises to buy under the same conditions.
 This arrangement is treated as a synallagmatic promise and is equivalent
 to a sales contract, although this interpretation has faced criticism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Legal implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Contractual value of pre-contractual documents: even advertisements and
 pre-contractual documents can have contractual value, as seen in a 2004
 ruling by the Cour de Cassation.
 Misrepresentations in such documents can lead to liability for misconduct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No constraining value after contract conclusion: once the definitive contract
 is concluded, the pre-contractual documents lose their binding force under
 specifically incorporated into the final agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exceptions: there are exceptions where the promise of a contract does not
 equate to the contract itself, particularly in cases involving loans and
 where adamages are sought as a remedy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Reiteraiton and consent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reiteration, the act of repeating the contract formalization process, typically
 in front of a notary, can sometimes be replaced by a court decision.
 Parties may also choose to include reiteration as an element of their consent,
 further solidifying the agreement's binding nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Formation of the Contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formation of a contract is a fundamental concept in contract law that
 outlines the conditions under which agreements become legally binding between
 parties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Article 1103 of the Civil Code establishes that contracts, once legally
 constituted, are binding upon the parties involved, acting as their law.
 This principle underscores the autonomy and the binding nature of contracts,
 highlighting the importance of agreements being formed in compliance with
 legal standards.
 It specifies four essential requirements for a contract's validity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Consent of the parties
\series default
: agreement must be made without coercion, mistake, or misrepresentation.
 Both parties must clearly and voluntarily agree to the contract terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Capacity to contract
\series default
: parties must have the legal ability to enter into a contract.
 This typically means they are of a certain age (usually 18 or older) and
 of sound mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Definite object
\series default
: the contract must have a clear subject matter or obejctive.
 This means the goods, services, or rights being exchanged are specified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Lawful cause
\series default
: the purpose and terms of the contract must be legal and not against public
 policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notably, Article 1108 does not mandate a specific form for the contract,
 allowing for flexibility in how agreements are made, whether orally, in
 writing, or through conduct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Voluntary Agreements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formation process emphasizes the voluntary nature of agreements, detailing
 how parties should conduct negotiations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Discussions
\series default
: the initial stage involves discussions, which are not the same as making
 a firm offer.
 It's an invitation to negotiate, marking the start of potential contract
 formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Invitation to start discussions
\series default
: this is distinct from a firm offer and serves as the initiation of negotiation
s, without committing either party.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Freedom to end negotiations
\series default
: parties are free to withdraw from talks at any time before an agreement
 is reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Obligations of good faith
\series default
: throughout the discussions, parties are expected to engage honestly and
 fairly, avoiding misleading or deceitful practices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Informing and cooling off period
\series default
: parties should inform each other about the terms and conditions of the
 proposed agreement.
 A cooling-off period may be allowed, giving parties time to reconsider
 their commitment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Effort to reach an agreement
\series default
: negotiations should aim to conclude with a mutual agreement, avoiding
 unnecessary delays or extensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Confidentiality
\series default
: respect for sensitive information shared during negotiations is crucial.
 Confidential details whould not be disclosed without consent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Limited tort liability
\series default
: while parties may be held liable for certain costs incurred during the
 negotiation phase, such as preliminary studies, they generally cannot be
 held responsible for the loss of an opportunity that never materialzied
 into a contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example of consent: two businesses agreeing to terms for a supply of goods
 after negotiations, where both parties clearly accept the terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example of capacity: an adult entering into a lease agreement for an apartment,
 having the legal age and mental ability to do so.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example of definitive object: a contract for the sale of a car, where the
 make, model, and year of the car are specified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example of lawful cause: a service contract for landscaping work, where
 the services to be provided are legal and have a legitimate purpose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Pollicitation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pollicitation refers to the act of making an offer in the context of contract
 formation.
 It is a key step in initiating contractual negotiations, setting out the
 terms under which the offeror is willing to enter into a contract.
 Let's break down the essential characteristics of a pollicitation and provide
 some clarity on its implications:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Firmness
\series default
: an offer must be firm, indicating the offeror's clear intention to be
 bound by the offer if accepted by the offeree.
 This means the offeror cannot withdraw the offer arbitrarily before the
 specified time period for acceptance has elapse or, if no time is specified,
 within a reasonable period.
 For example, a car dealership places an advertisement offering a specific
 model at a stated price, indicated the offer is valid until the end of
 the month.
 This is a firm offer because the dealership commits to the terms provided
 until the specified expiration date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Precision
\series default
: the offer must be precise, containing all the essential elements of the
 contract, notably the price.
 This precision ensures that, upon acceptance, there is a clear agreement
 on the contract's fundamental terms without the need for further negotiation.
 For example, an online retailer lists a product with a detailed description
 and price, making it clear what is being offered for sale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Express nature
\series default
: pollicitation must always be express, regardless of its form.
 It can be communicated in various ways, including written, oral, or even
 through conduct, such as displaying goods for sale in a public space.
 The key is that the offer must unambiguously indicate the offeror's intention
 to be bound.
 For example, a company sends a proposal to provide IT services to another
 business, detailing the scope of services and associated costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Public offer
\series default
: a public offer, one made to an unspecified audience, holds the same legal
 weight as an offer directed at a specific individual.
 The first party to accept such an offer in accordance with its terms effectivel
y enters into a contract with the offeror.
 For example, a restaurant displaying a sign outside offering a lunch special
 at a specific price.
 This is binding on the restaurant for anyone who enters and orders the
 special, fulfilling the conditions of the offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Reservations
\series default
: to mitigate the strictness of this rule, an offer can include certain
 reservations.
 For instance, the 
\emph on
intuitu peersonae
\emph default
 principle allows the offeror to stipulate that the acceptance must come
 from a party possessing specific qualities or qualifications deemed necessary
 for the contract's purpose.
 For example, a job posting requires applicants to have certain qualifications
 or experience, indicating that only those who meet these criteria are eligible
 to accept the offer of employment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Period of time
\series default
: an offer also includes a time frame for acceptance, which can be explicit
 or implicit, repending on the contract's nature or intended to be resonable.
 This period defines how long the offer remains open for acceptance, after
 which it may expire if not accepted.
 For example, the car sale previously mention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Regime Governing the Offer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regime governing the offer outlines the conditions under which an offer
 can be made, modified, or withdrawn, and the consequences of these actions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Retraction of the offer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, an offer is revocable, meaning the offeror can withdraw it before
 it is accepted.
 However, an offer becomes irrevocable if the offeror explicitly states
 the intention to not withdraw the offer for a certain period or under specific
 conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the offeror retracts an irrevocable offer, they may be liable for breach
 of the promise not to revoke the offer.
 This could lead to claims for damages by the offeree or enforcement of
 a penalty clause, if one was included in the offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the offeror retracts the offer during the period it was supposed to remain
 open (or before the offeree has had a reasonable time to consider it, in
 the absence of a specified period), this action constitutes a fault.
 If the cancellation causes damages to the offeree, the offeror may be held
 liable under tort responsibility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Public offers: the offeror can freely revoke a public offer unless it has
 been accepted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Specific person: if the offer targets a specific person, the offeror must
 allow a reasonable period for the offeree to examine and consider the offer
 before revocation, as established in a 2005 decision by the Cour de cassation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Lapse of termination of the offer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An offer becomes 
\series bold
obsolete
\series default
, meaning it stops producing effects, under certain conditions, such as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The death of the offeror.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The offeror undergoing bankruptcy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sudden incapacity of the offeror.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the offeree initially refuses the offer but then rapidly changes their
 mind, the initial refusal typically terminates the offer.
 However, the legal implications can vary based on the specifics of the
 situation and the timing of the change of mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jurisprudence is not clear regarding the effect of the offeror'sdeath within
 the specified time period for acceptance.
 Generally, unless the offer is of a personal nature or the contract specifies
 otherwise, the death of the offeror does not automatically revoke the offer
 before its expiration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Acceptance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acceptance is a crucial step in the formation of a contract, indicating
 the offeree's agreement to the terms proposed by the offeror.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Enlightened (Wise) acceptance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For acceptance to be valid, it must be informed.
 The offeree is presumed to be aware of and understand all clauses that
 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

readable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

usual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 within the context of the agreement.
 Clauses that fall outside of what's considered a tacit agreement are not
 deemed accepted unless proven otherwise.
 This ensures that acceptance is based on a full understanding of the terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a person signing a lease agreement is presumed to understand
 and accept all standard clauses that are clearly presented and typical
 for such agreements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Pure and simple
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acceptance must be unconditional and unambiguous.
 If the acceptance alters any terms of the offer, it is not considered a
 true acceptance but a counter-offer, which effectively nullifies the original
 offer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Tacit acceptance
\series default
: can be inferred from the actions of the parties, indicating agreement
 to the contract terms through conduct rather than explicit verbal or wirtten
 confirmation.
 For example, using a product or service without objection after receiving
 it can be interpreted as tacit acceptance of the sale terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Silence as acceptance
\series default
: generally, silence is not considered acceptance.
 This principle is particularly emphasized in consumer law to prevent practices
 such as forced sales at a distance.
 An exception exists when silence can be contextualized, such as in ongoing
 business relationships, or specific legal texts allow for it, or a letter
 confirms a previous verbal agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Contracts Between Absents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contracts between absents refer to agreements made when the offeror and
 offeree are not physically present together, often facilitated through
 communication technologies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
emission/reception theory
\series default
 addresses how and when a contract is formed between absent parties.
 The focus is on:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Emission theory
\series default
: a contract is considered formed when the offeror sends the acceptance,
 regardless of whether the offeree has received it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Reception theory
\series default
: a contract is only formed when the acceptance is received by the offeror.
 This approach is more common and practical, ensuring that the offeror is
 aware of the acceptance before being bound by it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if a freelancer sends an email accepting a project offer and
 the terms are received and acknowledged by the client, the contract is
 formed under the reception theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Practical implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Jurisdiction
\series default
: the location where the contract is considered completed can affect legal
 jurisdiction, which is important for determining the applicable laws and
 where legal actions can be initiated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Revocation of the offer
\series default
: challenges arise when an offer is revoked after acceptance has been sent
 but before it is received.
 The lack of clear jurisprudence on this matter requires judges to interpret
 the intent of the parties to determine if a contract was effectively formed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Electronic Contracts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The French Law on Confidence in the Digital Economy (LCEN), dated June 4,
 2004, and its subsequent modification on June 16, 2005, to transpose a
 European Directive from June 8, 2000, provide a regulatory framework for
 electronic contracts.
 These regulations are encapsulated within Articles 1369-1 to 1369-3 (and
 beyond) of the French Civil Code.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Electronic contracts
\series default
 are agreements where at least one party offers goods or services through
 electronic means, typically via the internet.
 This definition includes a broad range of commercial transactions conducted
 online, from e-commerce sales to service agreements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Key provisions and requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Article 1369-1: offer and technical conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The offer in an electronic contract must clearly detail the contractual
 terms and various technical conditions pertinent to digital transactions.
 These include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Contractual conditions: detailed description of goods or services, pricing,
 and terms of use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Technical conditions: steps for contract conclusion, mechanisms for identifying
 and correcting errors before submission, language of the contract, and
 rules regarding the archiving of contracts and commercial regulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Steps for contract conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law specifies that clear instructions must be provided on how to proceed
 through the different stages of entering into the contract.
 This ensures transparency and understanding for users navigating the contract
 formation process online.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Correction of errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There must be be technical means available for users to identify and correct
 any errors in their inputs before the final submission of their agreement.
 This feature is crucial for preventing misunderstandings or unintentional
 commitments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Contract language and archives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifications regarding the language used in the contract and how the contracts
 are archived offer additional clarity and security for both parties involved
 in the electronic transaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Professional and commercial rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The offer must also include any relevant professional or commercial rules,
 ensuring that parties are aware of the regulatory environment governing
 the transaction.
\end_layout

