\begin_layout Subsection
Defects in Consent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defects in consent are critical considerations in contract law that can
 affect the validity of a contract.
 These defects arise when the agreement between parties is influenced by
 factors that compromise the free and informed consent of one or more parties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preliminary Remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a contract to be valid, it must meet four fundamental conditions (Article
 1108):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Consent of the obliging party
\series default
: the party agreeing to the contract must do so willingly and knowingly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Capacity to contract
\series default
: parties must have the legal ability to enter into a contract, typically
 involving agre and mental competence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Definite object
\series default
: the contract must have a clear subject matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Lawful cause
\series default
: the purpose of the contract must be elgal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consent is considered valid only if it is given freely and without any defects.
 If consent is flawed, the contract may be deemed void.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certain individuals, such as those who are incapable (due to mental incapacity),
 dying persons, or illiterate individuals, may lack the ability to give
 valid consent.
 Originally, the concern oveer consent was particularly relevant to gifts
 but has been extended to all acts requiring legal capacity, as highlighted
 by Article 489, which states the necessity of being of sound mind to engage
 in valid legal acts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Objectives of protection and contractual security
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law aims to balance the protection of individuals with the need for
 contractual security.
 This includes safeguarding against 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lésion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
, where there's a significant imbalance between the obligations of the parties
 involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consent is not considered valid if it is affected by any of the following
 defects (Article 1109):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Mistake
\series default
: an error by one or more parties about a fundamental aspect of the contract.
 For example, a person buys a painting believing it to be an original work
 of a famous artist, but it turns out to be a false copy.
 The mistake about a fundamental aspect of the contract (the painting's
 authenticity) could nullify the agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Dol
\series default
: deception by one party to induce another to enter into the contract.
 For example, if a seller knowingly misrepresents a car's condition to a
 buyer, and the buyer relies on this misinformation when agreeing to the
 purchase, the contract could be voided due to fraud.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Violence
\series default
: coercion or undue pressure exerted on a party to force them into the contract.
 For example, threatening someone to sign a contract under threat of harm
 constitutes duress.
 Contracts signed under such conditions are voidable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Mistake
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
mistake
\series default
 occurs when one or both parties hold an incorrect belief about a critical
 fact at the time of contract formation.
 It is a commong ground for disputing the validity of a contract, because
 it indicates that the parties may not have reached a genuine agreement
 due to the error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Distinguishing between a mistake and a guarantee against hidden effects
 is crucial.
 A mistake pertains to an error in understanding or belief at the time of
 agreement, while a 
\series bold
guarantee against hidden effects
\series default
 deals with undisclosed flaws in the subject matter, that were not known
 at the time of sale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several types of mistake:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Mistake on the Substance 
\series default
(Article 1133):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
Objective and subjective evaluation
\bar default
: initially, the substance of a mistake was viewed objectively, focusing
 on whether a reasonable person would find the error significant.
 Over time, the assessment has become more subjective, considering whether
 the mistaken fact was a substantial quality important to the contracting
 party.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
Concrete VS Abstract Evaluation
\bar default
: the debate centers on whether the significance of the mistake should be
 evaluated in the specific context of the contract (
\emph on
in concreto
\emph default
) or based on general standards (
\emph on
in abstracto
\emph default
), affecting the burden of the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A notable case is 
